<% if @event_groups.length > 0 %>
  <div class="container logged">
    <section class="feed">
      <%= erb :_events, :layout => false %>

      <% if @page_number < 10 %>
        <a class="more" href="/page/<%= @page_number + 1 %>" data-url-pattern="/page/:number">More</a>
      <% end %>
    </section>
    <%= erb :_sidebar, :layout => false %>
  </div>
<% else %>
  <div class="container login">
    <article class="private col-1">
      <figure>
        <img src="/images/octofeed-animate.svg" alt="The Octofeed Icon">
        <figcaption>
          <ul>
            <li>Hello</li>
            <li>I am OctoFeed</li>
            <li>and I love GitHub</li>
            <li>*Easter egg*</li>
          </ul>
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
      <h1>Public & private events</h1>
      <p>The app gives read/write access to your repositories, commits and issues. Note that this is only used to <strong>see your private repos related events</strong>. We swear before the Octo God that it does not use its write privilege but if you don’t trust us, use the public one.</p>
      <a class="button login-with-gh" href="/auth/github_private"><span class="github-logo"></span> Login with GitHub</a>
    </article>
    <article class="public col-1">
      <h1>Public events only</h1>
      <p>Read-only app, <strong>only public events will be listed</strong>. We strongly suggest using the private login to maximise your experience.</p>
      <a class="button classy login-with-gh" href="/auth/github_public"><span class="github-logo"></span> Login with GitHub</a>
    </article>
    <div class="content">
      <article class="col-2">
        <h2>Disclaimer</h2>
        <p>This is an <strong>unofficial app and isn’t related with GtiHub</strong> in any way. It will look very familiar to you and is meant to be. We basically copied <a href="https://github.com/styleguide/css/1.0" title="GitHub CSS Styleguide 1.0">GitHub’s style</a> on purpose. We don’t want the environment to interfere in the experience.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="col-2">
        <h2>Information saved</h2>
        <p>The only thing being saved in a database is each of your events unique id to be able to implement the read/unread feature. No further information is saved. Read: If you use the “private app” version, we will not have any information on your private repos.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
    <%= erb :_sidebar, :layout => false %>
  </div>
<% end %>
